1
00:00:00,368 --> 00:00:12,403
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:14,307 --> 00:00:18,251
Okay, so I'm going to have some reflections on polarization.

3
00:00:19,193 --> 00:00:30,088
I've been on the old chat GTP, of course, and a couple of YouTubes, but I'm trying to get it within the sort of Dharma of the Buddha.

4
00:00:31,132 --> 00:00:37,301
So polarization often happens in times of change, on certain times people take positions.

5
00:00:38,823 --> 00:00:41,246
But this would be fine, say, for identity.

6
00:00:41,286 --> 00:00:53,804
So it's even on the bit that I researched, identity seems to be the primary cause for this polarization or the sort of foundation of it, you might say.

7
00:00:54,686 --> 00:00:59,112
Of course, that's at the root of suffering, according to the not-self doctrine of the Buddha.

8
00:00:59,582 --> 00:01:06,350
Each party thinks of itself as morally superior, hence more virtuous, more intelligent and, of course, more patriotic.

9
00:01:07,733 --> 00:01:18,647
This is the working of the self that thrives on comparison, not on the various definitions of, say, what virtue might be, but personalising and criticising the person.

10
00:01:19,748 --> 00:01:24,834
Hence the three conceits, I'm better, worse than you, and the more subtle conceit, I'm equal.

11
00:01:25,614 --> 00:01:28,459
The last one is what supports group identity.

12
00:01:29,165 --> 00:01:33,350
You find your companions and that group now compares itself with other groups.

13
00:01:33,551 --> 00:01:34,212
That's how it works.

14
00:01:35,493 --> 00:01:39,939
When it comes to immigration, for instance, we have those who accept it and even say we need more of it.

15
00:01:40,861 --> 00:01:45,248
And the opposite, of course, who say it's a conspiracy to replace the white race.

16
00:01:46,510 --> 00:01:51,115
So these people see each other as existential threats because they've personalised it.

17
00:01:52,158 --> 00:01:57,265
So disagreements are no longer about policy, just about the way, who you are.

18
00:01:58,527 --> 00:02:08,457
So now we as Dhammikas, so a Dhammika was the original way that the followers of the Buddha referred to themselves, followers of the true law.

19
00:02:09,560 --> 00:02:19,491
So we need to be aware when we're identifying with a group and not lose the objective perspective, which enables us to criticize their stance on any particular topic.

20
00:02:22,955 --> 00:02:24,096
For instance, if

21
00:02:24,480 --> 00:02:38,877
If there's a general agreement in the group that immigration has gone too far, especially since COVID, then we also need to know that there are changes happening in the European Convention of Human Rights, which also protect our own freedoms.

22
00:02:40,479 --> 00:02:47,207
Anyway, this leads to hardening of positions, moralising of areas such as public health, climate crisis and wealth.

23
00:02:48,128 --> 00:02:53,155
They become moral absolutes such that any compromise experienced as betrayal

24
00:02:54,754 --> 00:03:04,306
Because of the distortion of conceit, such positions fail to see that interconnectedness, interrelatedness, interdependence that we talk about.

25
00:03:05,288 --> 00:03:14,579
So, for instance, withdrawing aid, international aid, in other words, not sharing our wealth, leads to greater poverty.

26
00:03:14,778 --> 00:03:21,387
So it should not be a surprise that the numbers grow of people wanting to escape that very poverty and destitution.

27
00:03:23,122 --> 00:03:37,460
This fact that richer countries are reducing age also tells us about this neoliberal order and its economic system has allowed the market to rule without any social responsibility and follows the dictum, greed is good.

28
00:03:39,681 --> 00:03:48,353
The system has produced such uncertainty that more and more people are feeling their jobs are insecure, causing anxiety about loss of status and wealth.

29
00:03:48,956 --> 00:03:55,308
So such unhealthy and unwholesome mental states drive people to believe anyone who says they've got the answer.

30
00:03:57,593 --> 00:04:11,099
All these fears around such areas as loss of work, rising cost of living, immigration, climate, are all coupled with the growing despair that normal institutions are incapable of bettering the situation.

31
00:04:11,502 --> 00:04:23,634
So this leads to a loss of confidence in political parties, unions, religious organizations, other civic institutions that once were able to mediate and bring needed change.

32
00:04:24,495 --> 00:04:36,987
But it's no wonder that people start to join mass movements emotionally manipulated by demagogues and led by populists to deceive them into believing that they are working for the common good.

33
00:04:38,721 --> 00:04:42,925
What has made everything exponentially worse, of course, is social media.

34
00:04:43,305 --> 00:04:51,394
From the heady days when it was believed the internet would bring a harmonious world community, we're descending into a worldwide verbal brawl.

35
00:04:52,214 --> 00:04:55,398
At the moment it's words, but it soon could become violent action.

36
00:04:55,738 --> 00:04:59,502
So witness the storming of the capital by mega devotees.

37
00:05:01,223 --> 00:05:08,391
So the algorithms, the way they actually are, feed on our natural bent for threat and opposition.

38
00:05:08,692 --> 00:05:13,877
rather than having algorithms that help us to welcome and cooperate.

39
00:05:14,577 --> 00:05:20,404
They heard people in what's called epistemic silos, which sounds very good.

40
00:05:22,367 --> 00:05:30,415
Isolated groups of like-minded people that go on to intensify the situation, even to the point of conspiracies.

41
00:05:31,937 --> 00:05:36,182
So this, of course, has actually happened many times in history, you know, leading to civil wars.

42
00:05:36,843 --> 00:05:38,665
Europe's been full of civil wars.

43
00:05:39,235 --> 00:05:43,278
Anyway, such an occasion happened in our little tiny village of Whitegrit.

44
00:05:44,240 --> 00:05:53,449
A neighbour working for the Shropshire Council in England to bring more wealth to the area won a grant, I think it was a million pounds actually, from the lottery fund.

45
00:05:54,168 --> 00:06:00,475
A local eco-warrior saw this as a danger to turning the area into a holiday resort.

46
00:06:01,536 --> 00:06:06,440
There were meetings and finally a confrontation with the lottery fund grant receiver.

47
00:06:07,601 --> 00:06:12,187
Young men used foul language, happily stamped out by a retired magistrate.

48
00:06:14,029 --> 00:06:15,771
And eventually everything calmed down.

49
00:06:16,952 --> 00:06:21,798
In the meantime, an email was sent full of expletives calling on resistance.

50
00:06:23,982 --> 00:06:26,944
Frankly, the whole fracas was beyond pathetic.

51
00:06:26,964 --> 00:06:29,949
To this day, I haven't seen any change and still wonder what happened to the money.

52
00:06:31,230 --> 00:06:32,632
But all the markers were there.

53
00:06:33,733 --> 00:06:34,875
Model outraged.

54
00:06:36,238 --> 00:06:39,543
What right of the Shropshire Council to do this to us?

55
00:06:39,663 --> 00:06:41,365
We're in Powys, Wales.

56
00:06:42,946 --> 00:06:46,029
Simplified narrative, it's going to ruin the area.

57
00:06:46,810 --> 00:06:49,632
Conspiracy theories, what else are the council going to do?

58
00:06:50,553 --> 00:06:51,776
And group validation.

59
00:06:53,057 --> 00:06:55,019
I was told the meeting at the pub went very well.

60
00:06:55,779 --> 00:07:04,069
It's a wonder they didn't turn up to the meeting armed with picks, shovels and trowels, the local population being farmers and retired well-to-do.

61
00:07:05,163 --> 00:07:08,505
But what stays with me is the amount of anger that it generated.

62
00:07:09,127 --> 00:07:09,726
Quite weird.

63
00:07:13,029 --> 00:07:19,716
The consequences of these silos is that they are groups that create realities that cannot exist with other realities.

64
00:07:19,896 --> 00:07:21,759
That's the problem with conspiracies.

65
00:07:22,418 --> 00:07:30,627
This is also a consequence of the postmodernism that questioned objective truth, declaring we all have our own realities, hence all is relative.

66
00:07:31,266 --> 00:07:34,089
So we move to post-truth and, of course, outright lying.

67
00:07:35,403 --> 00:07:38,767
Now, the Buddha taught the whole of the spiritual life was good companionship.

68
00:07:38,987 --> 00:07:41,071
We're interdependent beings.

69
00:07:41,091 --> 00:07:43,295
And of course, the obverse is also true.

70
00:07:43,314 --> 00:07:45,016
A den of thieves.

71
00:07:45,817 --> 00:07:52,228
Good companionship, inverted commas, is also necessary to invoke false narratives and conspiracies.

72
00:07:53,129 --> 00:08:02,423
The disturbing fact is that feedback loops intensify since thoughts feed on thoughts, emotions on emotions.

73
00:08:03,297 --> 00:08:30,250
and ready with ready backing from social media and the rewards of finding such friends the feeling of safety emotional support and ideological fantasizing now the buddha tells us about this inner process very clearly and how it how it very clearly produces proliferation the pali word is papancha which i particularly like a lot of papancha sense consciousness

74
00:08:30,786 --> 00:08:39,075
arises from the base of the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and the mind, heart, and it's dependent on those senses.

75
00:08:40,255 --> 00:08:46,701
So when you have an object and a sense base and consciousness, that's what he calls contact.

76
00:08:46,721 --> 00:08:48,844
Contact is a requirement for feeling.

77
00:08:49,443 --> 00:08:51,466
What we feel, we perceive.

78
00:08:52,307 --> 00:08:54,349
What we perceive, we think about.

79
00:08:55,350 --> 00:08:57,672
What we think about, we proliferate.

80
00:08:57,904 --> 00:09:05,452
What we proliferate is the source of which judgments driven by proliferating perceptions beset a person.

81
00:09:06,313 --> 00:09:07,975
And this occurs on all the senses.

82
00:09:08,937 --> 00:09:15,783
For those of you who are interested, that's from the Honeyball discourse in the Middle End Sayings, number 18.

83
00:09:19,607 --> 00:09:27,777
So the same process is magnified between people so that moral outrage rewarded by groups leads to certainty and the group reinforces itself.

84
00:09:28,162 --> 00:09:33,908
by denigrating the opposite groups, leading to a loss of empathy and to a loss of communication.

85
00:09:34,428 --> 00:09:41,236
So this distrust simply leads to a hardening of positions, especially where the others are seen as potential threats.

86
00:09:43,119 --> 00:09:47,203
And again, there's the emotional rewards of like-minded friends.

87
00:09:47,823 --> 00:09:52,870
So how can we do something to reverse the process or at least undermine it?

88
00:09:55,297 --> 00:09:59,623
So we have here the basic cause, light and identity, how people define themselves.

89
00:09:59,844 --> 00:10:13,503
And this identity narrows to a particular cause, creating a barrier that expels anyone who disagrees and then places verbal and other weapons on the barrier to destroy those it describes as enemies.

90
00:10:14,825 --> 00:10:22,076
For such alienated group, one is to point to a higher identity that embraces, to some extent, those of other parties.

91
00:10:22,876 --> 00:10:25,000
This is the work of politics, of course,

92
00:10:25,755 --> 00:10:32,143
So when it comes to immigration, for instance, both sides of the argument need to be lifted to a greater overall view of the situation.

93
00:10:33,544 --> 00:10:40,392
And this can be done through the very media that supports polarisation by bringing opposing groups to dispute in the open.

94
00:10:41,092 --> 00:10:47,919
No matter how distasteful we may find some of the people, they need to be engaged in open debate.

95
00:10:50,783 --> 00:10:55,087
There's also the benefit of citizen assemblies that have been used to great effect in Ireland.

96
00:10:56,806 --> 00:10:59,471
I don't know why we don't have them in the UK, by the way.

97
00:10:59,631 --> 00:11:00,173
Just weird.

98
00:11:01,095 --> 00:11:02,798
Perhaps the government finds them threatening.

99
00:11:04,503 --> 00:11:10,316
So when we identify with a cause, everything becomes saturated with me and me is always right.

100
00:11:10,777 --> 00:11:14,224
We might refer to this as ego, but I prefer the old word pride.

101
00:11:15,283 --> 00:11:21,773
It finds it's hard to compromise and any giving in to the opposition is seen as a sort of shaming betrayal.

102
00:11:22,274 --> 00:11:32,268
But once we soften the grip and admit that no one has total exclusive truth and open up to another's views, compromise allows a wise solution.

103
00:11:33,649 --> 00:11:38,777
These are perspectives that can accommodate different views.

104
00:11:39,597 --> 00:11:42,422
Enemies can become people we can discuss and argue with.

105
00:11:43,515 --> 00:11:45,038
And there's our Dharma practice.

106
00:11:45,578 --> 00:11:55,554
Now, as ordinary citizens, we need to make our views known to politicians, to our local MP, whenever possible, encourage the government to control media content.

107
00:11:56,596 --> 00:12:02,245
We also need to be sensitive to journalists to make sure we know who are non-partisan and independent.

108
00:12:02,787 --> 00:12:05,370
We need to be able to tell facts from comment.

109
00:12:06,412 --> 00:12:11,159
And when it comes to media, you know, to limit the amount and type we allow into our hearts.

110
00:12:13,755 --> 00:12:15,918
Now, we also have to admit to our biases.

111
00:12:16,500 --> 00:12:21,086
Biases can be explicit, we're aware of them, or implicit, we're not aware of them.

112
00:12:21,947 --> 00:12:25,673
Prejudices, meanwhile, are those biases that we're actively developing.

113
00:12:26,836 --> 00:12:30,360
Acknowledging biases allows us to counteract their effect.

114
00:12:31,142 --> 00:12:39,014
It's virtually impossible not to have religious, racial, gender and class bias.

115
00:12:39,114 --> 00:12:41,096
It's in the DNA of our culture.

116
00:12:42,004 --> 00:12:47,210
We may find that difficult to accept, but unless we're aware of them, they'll affect our behavior.

117
00:12:47,910 --> 00:12:54,658
And we may be embarrassed by Freudian slips and suddenly becoming self-defensive or aggressive when accused.

118
00:12:55,759 --> 00:13:05,688
So practicing method is not just a contemplative practice, but approaching people or media we are strongly against with a heart that is open to understanding where they come from.

119
00:13:05,729 --> 00:13:10,594
And it would really help to find a discussion group online, better in person.

120
00:13:11,350 --> 00:13:18,236
where we can bring up, which are set to bring people of differing views into dialogue with each other.

121
00:13:21,259 --> 00:13:26,765
This leads us to realizing that it is destructive to shame other people.

122
00:13:28,447 --> 00:13:30,389
Like, for instance, saying they're ignorant.

123
00:13:30,870 --> 00:13:32,932
This happened after the Brexit referendum.

124
00:13:33,833 --> 00:13:37,898
And there's no point in showering people with facts if they don't trust us.

125
00:13:39,042 --> 00:13:48,636
The wisest thing is to follow the Buddha's own approach, which was to understand the other's position and questioning it before launching into our own views and opinions.

126
00:13:50,559 --> 00:13:53,443
So polarization isn't something new.

127
00:13:53,985 --> 00:13:55,187
It can lead to civil wars.

128
00:13:55,267 --> 00:13:57,149
It's done in many countries in the past.

129
00:13:57,831 --> 00:14:07,446
And it's our task to be sure that we're not fueling this malignancy that has the danger of metastasizing into a general conflict that's of no benefit to anybody.

130
00:14:09,181 --> 00:14:15,809
So what do we do when a racist, sexist, religious, gender or any other bias thought comes into the mind?

131
00:14:16,610 --> 00:14:21,298
We might find ourselves feeling guilty and push the thought away without really accepting it.

132
00:14:22,759 --> 00:14:28,928
So that conditioning has not been allowed to manifest and continues to fester.

133
00:14:28,948 --> 00:14:35,037
If we allow the bias to manifest in our minds and hearts, then we can begin to undermine it.

134
00:14:35,977 --> 00:14:37,460
First, there's the acceptance.

135
00:14:37,539 --> 00:14:39,123
This is a bias in my heart.

136
00:14:39,663 --> 00:14:42,548
And once I accept it, we can recognize it as unwholesome.

137
00:14:44,009 --> 00:14:50,658
Now, usually because it arises because we've seen or heard someone whom the bias hates.

138
00:14:51,360 --> 00:14:55,666
So we can bring that person to mind, see the situation from their point of view.

139
00:14:56,047 --> 00:15:01,335
We can apologize to them as an active drama practice within ourselves.

140
00:15:02,296 --> 00:15:05,039
Then we can hold the person in a caring embrace.

141
00:15:05,543 --> 00:15:07,667
You can't hate and care at the same time.

142
00:15:08,687 --> 00:15:12,654
Sometimes you have to be creative with this process of undermining biases.

143
00:15:14,979 --> 00:15:26,217
If we're sitting in meditation and we get one of these biases coming up, you might find it just as useful to just sit with the aversion, just the feeling of the aversion.

144
00:15:27,294 --> 00:15:32,403
And what we're doing, we're just allowing that bad energy to exhaust itself.

145
00:15:32,423 --> 00:15:44,184
And then if we stay to the very end, when that feeling of aversion comes to an end, we stay to the point where it disappears, you might experience it transforming into the opposite.

146
00:15:44,445 --> 00:15:49,934
So you might suddenly find your heart full of love or peacefulness or some other positive state.

147
00:15:50,655 --> 00:15:51,597
Nothing's lost.

148
00:15:51,932 --> 00:15:58,582
in allowing these negative states to come up and pass away, they're always changing towards their opposites.

149
00:15:58,602 --> 00:16:13,245
This we find in the right attitude of the Eightfold Path, which is stated as going from greed to generosity, hatred to love, and cruelty to compassion.

150
00:16:14,206 --> 00:16:20,876
It happens naturally in the meditation, as long as we allow the heart to have full freedom to express itself.

151
00:16:24,451 --> 00:16:25,011
Very good.

152
00:16:25,052 --> 00:16:30,081
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that they have not caused confusion.

153
00:16:30,142 --> 00:16:32,846
Write to me if it does, by the way.

154
00:16:32,866 --> 00:16:39,438
And that by your practice, you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

